{"questionId":"28001","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>A company makes doors for kitchen cupboards from two layers. The inside layer is wood,&nbsp;and its thickness is normally distributed with mean <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>7</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>mm</mtext></math> and standard deviation <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>mm</mtext></math>.&nbsp;The outside layer is plastic, and its thickness is normally distributed with mean <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>mm</mtext></math> and&nbsp;standard deviation <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>16</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>mm</mtext></math>. The thickness of the plastic is independent of the thickness of&nbsp;the wood.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the probability that a randomly chosen door has a total thickness of less than <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>9</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>mm</mtext></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>wood layer,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>W</mi><mo>~</mo><mtext>N</mtext><mfenced><mrow><mn>7</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><msup><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced></math>; plastic&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>P</mi><mo>~</mo><mtext>N</mtext><mfenced><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><msup><mn>16</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced></math></p>\n<p>door:&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>X</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>W</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>P</mi></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>E</mtext><mfenced><mi>X</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mtext>mm</mtext></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 